Hey, #highered people of twitter!
What are you reading right now? 
What do you recommend to those looking to explore the world of #highereducation a bit more?

These points aren't to say that #HigherEd is 'dead' or irreparably flawed. And a piece like this, pointing out positives, may help balance our discussions a bit. 

But it shouldn't lead us to ignore real concerns, and we should take criticism seriously to improve the field. (6/6)

Relatedly, this piece makes no real mention of access or cost, besides noting that the costs are increasing and that students continue to bear them.

What does it say about our #HigherEd "golden age" if it's predicated on debt and exclusion? (5/6)

The article also raises great points about the growth of #research funding, especially federal.

At the same time, the author makes no real mention of another funding issue - the relative diminishment of state #HigherEd funding and what this means for public universities. (4/6)

On the topic of growth, enrollment increases (& corresponding growth of large universities) is held up as a positive too.

Maybe it is. However, we also need to consider this within the context of social pressure, corresponding cost, and completion rates. #HigherEd (3/6)

For example, the author hails the growth of faculty numbers over the last few decades...without engaging with the growth of adjunct faculty & short-term contracts and what this means for the future (and present) of #HigherEd. (2/6)

Thread: An interesting @ChronicleReview piece challenging the "decline of #HigherEd" idea. While there are great points (research $, enrollment, R&D, etc.), the article seems to avoid many of the main criticisms, to its detriment. (1/6)
